{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"75b0d7a0-a3ab-4822-887b-cbee2af73855","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — found in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. They contain the stack trace, exception type, and faulting address.\n\n2. **Core dumps** — disabled by default. Enable with:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically appears in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the `.ips` report.\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually the quickest way to start investigating without `createdump`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"474503a5-339f-45a4-9f50-e8dbab1b6633","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":250,"requestId":"DA0A:AAEEE:542081:5FCFCC:6A03D867"},"id":"c57c559e-5595-43b4-947a-6e0423c7226c","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:48:30.638Z","parentId":"260fac64-3e8e-424e-b9d6-90c179050646"}
